umentation','en','Number',NULL,NULL,0,0),(375,'form_number_label_documentation','en','Label for the form component',NULL,NULL,0,0),(376,'form_number_suffix_documentation','en','The type of the number e.g. USD, Kg, etc.',NULL,NULL,0,0),(377,'suffix','en','Suffix',NULL,NULL,0,0),(378,'form_number_decimal_places_documentation','en','Number of decimal places to show.',NULL,NULL,0,0),(379,'decimal_places','en','Decimal Places',NULL,NULL,0,0),(380,'resource_documentation_group_separator','en','A group separator, like a comma (,) or a dot (.), helps to organize big numbers into easier-to-read groups, usually of three digits. For example, the number 1,000 or 1.000 means one thousand. It separates thousands from hundreds, making it quicker to read and understand the value. Different places use different symbols as group separators.',NULL,NULL,0,0),(381,'resource_form_number_title_group_separator','en','Group Separator',NULL,NULL,0,0),(382,'resource_documentation_decimal_separator','en','A decimal separator is a dot (.), comma (,), or other symbols that divide a number into whole and fractional parts. Like in 12.34 or 12,34. In $3.50, the dot (.) is the decimal separator which means you have 3 dollars and 50 cents.',NULL,NULL,0,0),(383,'resource_form_number_title_decimal_separator','en','Decimal Separator',NULL,NULL,0,0),(384,'resource_documentation_group_separator_characters_count','en','The group separator character count indicates how many digits are grouped together before a separator is used. The most common grouping is by thousands (3 characters), but some regions or systems allow for customization, such as grouping by ten thousand (4 characters). Three characters grouping (1,000 or 1.000): This is widely used globally. Four characters grouping (10,000 or 10.000): This is less common but can be found in certain East Asian countries.',NULL,NULL,0,0),(385,'resource_form_number_title_group_separator_characters_count','en','Group Number',NULL,NULL,0,0),(386,'resource_form_n